to clarify things..

We have an index for the zipkin span json, called `zipkin-2016-08-14`. Span documents have a nullable timestamp field, but it is in epoch microseconds, not milliseconds. Basically, it is stored as a long.
Ex. 

``` json
{
  "traceId": "3b47c02255029f91",
  "name": "client-calls-server-via-post",
  "id": "3b47c02255029f91",
  "timestamp": 1455242412402125,
  "duration": 9441,
  "annotations": [],
  "binaryAnnotations": [
    {
      "key": "jaegerClient",
      "value": "Python-0.7.9"
    },
    {
      "key": "lc",
      "value": "client",
      "endpoint": {
        "serviceName": "client",
        "ipv4": "127.0.0.1"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

We want to index on span.timestamp/1000, via a date attribute or otherwise that Kibana can read, but that isn't stored back into the original document json (ideally). In the above example, where .timestamp=1455242412402125 (epoch micros), the one for kibana would be 1455242412402 (epoch millis).

Here's our [index template](https://github.com/openzipkin/zipkin/blob/master/zipkin-storage/elasticsearch/src/main/resources/zipkin/storage/elasticsearch/zipkin_template.json). Can someone help us figure out what to do?
